# NET-NEW under lead-m0uy (→ shopsystem-templates), pinning the UPDATE half of the
# single ops-coordinates artifact. Scenario 211 (@scenario_hash:0a3a8267109b5792)
# pins that "shop-templates bootstrap" RENDERS "bin/ops-coordinates" via the
# render-tokens path; there was NO update-path renderer, so an existing repo (the
# lead, or any adopter past its first bootstrap) running "shop-templates update" to
# adopt v0.46.0 got the drift advisories for the shop-owned ops files but NEVER
# received "bin/ops-coordinates" — yet the canonical v0.46.0 "bin/shop-shell" does
# "source bin/ops-coordinates" and references OPS_FRAMEWORK_IMAGE with NO literal
# fallback (scenario 205, @scenario_hash:1885dea2b4550fde). So the canonical ops
# scripts could not be adopted via update. This scenario pins that update PRODUCES
# the artifact for an existing repo, with the same ADR-043 D2 content contract as
# bootstrap (211).
#
# RENDERED, not drift-advised — decision recorded here for the architect: scenarios
# 139 (@scenario_hash:3c496f8858b6b033) and 140 (@scenario_hash:29caed838aebe9f7)
# place "compose.yaml" and "bin/shop-shell" in the shop-OWNED bucket (update does
# not touch them; only advises on drift) because adopters are expected to customize
# them. "bin/ops-coordinates" is a DIFFERENT kind of file: a derived single-source
# artifact whose values come from the manifest "product:" root and whose ONLY
# customization path is environment override (each OPS_* key is env-overridable per
# 211), NOT hand-editing. That is the managed-render contract (cf. the lead
# skill-group re-pour, scenarios 162-164), not the shop-owned contract. So update
# RENDERS/refreshes it rather than advising. This does NOT conflict with 139/140:
# those enumerate a DIFFERENT file set (compose.yaml, bin/shop-shell); ops-coordinates
# is not in the shop-owned drift-advised bucket. This scenario pins only the
# create-if-absent case (the actual gap — existing repos have NOTHING); a stale-refresh
# case, if wanted, is a separate behavior/scenario.
#
# COEXIST (by hash): 211 (@0a3a8267109b5792, bootstrap RENDER counterpart) remains
# VALID — this is its update counterpart; 204 (@b7ea0de32ef49854) and 205
# (@1885dea2b4550fde, shop-shell SOURCES the artifact) remain VALID consumers;
# 139 (@3c496f8858b6b033) and 140 (@29caed838aebe9f7, shop-owned non-touch / drift
# advisory for compose.yaml + bin/shop-shell) remain VALID and are NOT contradicted —
# their file set does not include bin/ops-coordinates.
#
# ARCHITECT FLAG (do NOT act here — PO authoring only): scenario 174
# (@scenario_hash:f7af63457d95962f) enumerates the bootstrap ops file-set as EXACTLY
# FIVE shop-owned files with an exclusivity premise and does not yet include
# "bin/ops-coordinates"; the same 174-growth follow-up flagged on 211 (cf. lead-y9e2)
# governs there. Not edited here.
#
# @bc: and the reproducing @scenario_hash on dispatch are the Architect's; the
# block-only @scenario_hash below is the PO's authoring hash.
@scenario_hash:4c646ae20a1540e3
Scenario: "shop-templates update" against an existing "lead" shop that has no "bin/ops-coordinates" renders the single shell-sourceable ops-coordinates artifact for it — derived from the manifest "product:" root and carrying the same ADR-043 D2 content contract the bootstrap render-tokens path produces (scenario 211, @scenario_hash:0a3a8267109b5792) — so that after "update" an existing repo (past its first bootstrap) has a sourceable "bin/ops-coordinates" matching what "bootstrap" would write, and the canonical "bin/shop-shell" that sources it with no literal fallback no longer resolves OPS_FRAMEWORK_IMAGE or the other coordinate keys empty; ops-coordinates is a derived single-source artifact that update RENDERS, not a hand-edited shop-owned script it only advises on (contrast scenarios 139 and 140)
  Given an existing git repository at a target directory "/tmp/example-lead-shop" that was previously bootstrapped as a "lead" shop named "shopsystem-product"
  And the target directory contains no file at "bin/ops-coordinates" (the pre-artifact adoption state of a repo bootstrapped before the artifact existed)
  When I invoke the "shop-templates" update entry point against the target directory "/tmp/example-lead-shop"
  Then the exit code is 0
  And after the invocation the target directory contains a file at "bin/ops-coordinates" not under any ".claude/" subdirectory
  And the byte contents of "bin/ops-coordinates" equal what the "shop-templates" bootstrap render-tokens path writes to "bin/ops-coordinates" for shop type "lead" and shop name "shopsystem-product" — the same ADR-043 D2 content contract pinned by scenario 211 (@scenario_hash:0a3a8267109b5792)
  And sourcing "bin/ops-coordinates" in a bash shell succeeds with exit code 0 and defines the shell variables OPS_SLUG, OPS_NETWORK, OPS_POSTGRES_CONTAINER, OPS_VAULT_CONTAINER, OPS_VAULT_NAME, OPS_BROKER_ADDR, OPS_POSTGRES_PORT, OPS_VAULT_API_PORT, OPS_VAULT_PROXY_PORT, OPS_DATA_ROOT, OPS_LEAD_BEADS_REPO, OPS_BC_BEADS_REPO_FMT, OPS_ORG, and OPS_FRAMEWORK_IMAGE
  And after sourcing with no override environment set, OPS_BC_BEADS_REPO_FMT resolves to "shopsystem-{bc}-beads" (the slug-strip contract of scenario 211, @scenario_hash:0a3a8267109b5792, applies "_ops_slug" to the shop name "shopsystem-product" yielding slug "shopsystem") with the literal "{bc}" placeholder intact, and OPS_FRAMEWORK_IMAGE resolves to a non-empty value, so the canonical "bin/shop-shell" that sources this artifact with no literal fallback resolves neither an empty launch image nor a placeholder-destroyed beads-repo format
